timeInRangesReport.body: Time In Ranges provides a graph showing the percentage of time your Sensor glucose readings were above, below, or within certain glucose ranges. The Custom graph is based on your Target Glucose Range, and the Standard graph is based on a target range of 70 to 180 mg/dL.
timeInRangesReport.title: Time in Ranges

dailyPatternsReport.body:
The Daily Patterns graph shows the pattern and variability of your glucose readings, from your Sensor, over a typical day. Here’s how to read the graph:

  • The thick line shows your glucose readings’ median (midpoint).

  • The shaded area closest to the line shows the 25-75 percentile range of your readings.

  • The shaded area farthest from the line shows the 5-95 percentile range of your readings.

Note: Daily Patterns needs at least 5 days of glucose data.
dailyPatternsReport.title: Daily Patterns

firstImpactScore.body: Your predicted impact has been updated to show the actual impact the food had on your glucose, calculated from sensor data after you ate or drank. Other factors, such as medication, exercise, and stress can also have an impact on your glucose data.
firstImpactScore.body2: Glucose impact shows up in your Libre Assist feed within a few hours of eating.
firstImpactScore.title: How we measure glucose impact

concatenatedScore.body: When meals, snacks and drinks happen close together, the actual impact on your glucose is calculated the same for each food you had in that time period.
concatenatedScore.body2: The food you had before is a factor in how the next thing you eat or drink impacts you, just like medication, exercise, or stress can be a factor in how your food impacts you.
concatenatedScore.title: Combined glucose impact

step1.body: Snap a picture to get quick AI-generated feedback on your food and tips to lower its predicted impact.
step1.title: Make better meal choices in the moment

step2.body: After you eat or drink, check back to see how food actually impacted your glucose, based on your sensor data.
step2.title: Understand how food really impacts you

aiWarningSection.body: Libre Assist uses generative artificial intelligence to produce predicted food scores and tips to lower glucose impact, and this info isn’t always correct. Always make dietary choices in reference to your best judgment and the advice of your healthcare team.
aiWarningSection.body2: AI-generated predictions and tips are based only on food and don’t take into account other factors such as sensor data or insulin doses.
aiWarningSection.title: AI-generated insights aren‘t always correct

glucoseImpactSection.body: Glucose impact is based on sensor data. Keep in mind other factors besides food can raise or lower glucose—like physical activity, stress, and medication and alcohol.
glucoseImpactSection.body2: This means the predicted impact of your food may not always match its actual glucose impact.
glucoseImpactSection.title: Actual glucose impact may not match predicted impact

medicalAdviceSection.body: Don’t use Libre Assist as a substitute for professional medical advice, including personalized dietary and dosing guidance.
medicalAdviceSection.body2: Consult a health care professional or registered dietician for nutritional recommendations tailored to your individual needs and circumstances.
medicalAdviceSection.title: Libre Assist is not intended for medical advice

phoneWarningsIosScreen.body:
OS Features

  • Do not use Require Passcode or Require Face ID for your {{ descriptiveAppName }} at this time.

  • If you use the iOS Screen Time feature, add {{ descriptiveAppName }} to the list of Always Allowed apps.

  • If using Scheduled Summary:

    1. Do not add {{ descriptiveAppName }} to the “Apps in Summary” List.

    2. Set the {{ descriptiveAppName }} Notification Delivery to “Immediate Delivery” in your OS settings.

  • If using Focus, add {{ descriptiveAppName }} to the list of apps in Allowed Notifications.

  • Your app must be running in the background. If you restart your phone, open your App to make sure it’s working properly.

  • If using StandBy Mode, turn on Show Notifications in your Standby Mode OS settings.

  • Do not use Assistive Access mode at this time.


OS Updates

  • Disable automatic OS updates.

  • After an OS update, open the App and check your device settings to make sure it's working properly.
